If you want to group by multiple fields you can create a record that encapsulates that grouping:

    record DepartmentGender(String department, String gender) {
      DepartmentGender(Employee employee) {
        this(employee.getDepartment(), employee.getGender());
      }
    }

If record is unavailable you can implement your own custom class (or you could use a third-party library such as [Tuple][1] from Apache):

    class DepartmentGender {
      String department;
      String gender;

      DepartmentGender(Employee employee) {
        department = employee.getDepartment();
        gender = employee.getGender();
      }
    
      @Override
      public String toString() {
        return String.format(&quot;%s (%s)&quot;, department, gender);
      }
    
      @Override
      public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (o == this)
          return true;
        if (!(o instanceof DepartmentGender))
          return false;
        DepartmentGender other = (DepartmentGender)o;
        return (other.department.equals(department)) &amp;&amp; (other.gender.equals(gender));
      }
    
      @Override
      public int hashCode() {
        return department.hashCode() * gender.hashCode();
      }
    }

